\begin_layout Standard
Sousuke pulled down his visor.
 A freezing gust of wind buffeted against his face suddenly; it made him
 swivel around like someone had slapped him, lose his balance and fall on
 his back, fresh powdery snow going up in a small silver cloud around him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bjorn laughed with hands crossed over his chest and a carefully constructed
 grin on his face.
 Once Sousuke was back on his feet, he slapped him across the back and started
 walking towards the crawler, shaking his head.
 Half-way there he paused to pick up the surveyor unit; he brushed some
 snow off his beard, powered down the panel, folded the telescopic legs
 and placed the very expensive piece of eqipment across his shoulders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A glimpse at Sousuke almost struggling to walk upwind; another shake of
 the head, and a laughter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everyone laughed at the new guy, that much was to be expected.
 It was actually a sign of good mental health.
 Practical jokes and a tendency to make fun of every little thing were commonpla
ce, working this far north of civilization.
 Except Sousuke had been stationed in Field Zeta for three years, no rotation.
 It hadn't grown on him; it made him sick.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three weeks of leave each year, that was it.
 That was his lifeline with the world that despite the climate change and
 the Big Melt of '33 and the Disconnect of '35, still had beautiful warm
 beaches filled with young girls in miniscule bikinis.
 Even in Hokkaido in November.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three hours by helicopter to Spitsbergen, then a four-hour flight to Murmansk
 to the Roskosmos SSTO.
 From there on, it was a three-hour suborbital flight to almost any place
 on Earth.
 And still, when it came time to buy that ticket, he always flew to Sapporo.
 He somehow always wanted to see the half-sunken family house at Nemuro,
 the cherry tree orchards sitting right beneath the surface like dead corals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He put on his best effort at a smile and gave a thumbs up to Bjorn.
 He suddenly wished there was some other way to go about it, but he had
 committed himself.
 Everything was going to change, soon enough.
 Perhaps even overnight and hopefully for the better.
 It wasn't for him to fret about though; he would do his part and then they
 would either fail or succeed.
 There could be no middle ground, no chance at negotiating or talking things
 over once it went down.
 Not even if they wanted to.
 No failsafe, no human factor.
 Except himself, of course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bjorn shouted at him from the relative comfort of the crawler, a lit smoke
 already in hand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Don't just stand there! Come on! Checkpoints, more checkpoints!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a reason that was wholly above and beyond Sousuke's understanding, Bjorn
 seemed to relish in the job of running around in a snow crawler in the
 undecided day or night of the Arctic, searching almost blindly for thorium
 deposits in the faceless white desert of the Arctic.
 Perhaps it was the rush of discovery, or the associated finder's fee.
 Perhaps it was just Bjorn being Norwegian.
 Robots might have been able to do the job better, cheaper, and a whole
 lot warmer for any humans involved in the process.
 But they couldn't be trusted, not like regular folk itching for a chance
 to live the life.
 Anything that could transmit and receive couldn't be trusted these days.
 The Disconnect had made sure of that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sousuke jumped inside the crawler, closed the door behind him, reached for
 his thermo and poured a cup of almost scalding hot tea.
 He didn't sip, he just held on to it for the warmth.
 Bjorn started the engine and focused his attention on the control panel,
 waiting for the 'Engine Ready' sign to light up.
 He drew a puff from his cigarette and offered Sousuke one, purely from
 habit.
 Sousuke shook his head, still wearing the heavy fur-lined hood: real fur,
 an overpriced luxury, never mind banned by the UN, or what it lately voted
 to call itself the Earth Coalition.
 As if the name `United Nations' somehow offended the Big Three.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He relaxed a bit into the seat, stretching his legs.
 The cabin of the crawler was spacious, but spartan.
 He'd turned an empty display socket into a small sort of basket.
 There was a small nook somewhere in the plastic that doubled as a cup holder.
 Sousuke placed the cup there and closed his eyes for a moment.
 The engine revved up suddenly, making the crawler lurch forward like a
 startled beast.
 The tea spilled; Sousuke looked at Bjorn who simply shrugged and drove
 on through the snow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

There's more where that came from, no?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Bjorn said with a mischievous grin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You could have asked,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 replied Sousuke tersely.
 Bjorn retorted in an equally dry manner, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You could have offered me one.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I thought you didn't like tea,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Sousuke with a frown.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Still,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 came the bleak answer.
\end_layout

